<Verbatim PAsource="" >SMITH </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >was cleared of murdering tragic </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Sarah Crump </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >at the Old Bailey in 1993 after his lawyer accused police of a "scandalous cover-up".
</New>

<New PAsource="" >QC Ronald Thwaites said officers had failed to disclose information about other fingerprints found in Sarah's flat because they were certain they had the right man.
</New>

<New PAsource="" >Medical receptionist </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Sarah, </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >33, who was pregnant, had been secretly working as a call girl from her home in Southall, West London. </New>
<New PAsource="" >Her killer cut off her breasts and carried out other mutilations, matching surgical scars on the body of a woman Smith was obsessed with. </New>
<New PAsource="" >When he walked free from court horrified relatives of </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Sarah</Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >, convinced he was guilty, sobbed: "He'll be back."
</New>

<Verbatim PAsource="" >Detective Inspector Jill McTigue</Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >, who led the hunt for Sarah's killer, was severely criticised after the case. </New>
<New PAsource="" >It was a blow to the police, who believed Smith could go on to become a serial killer after a lifetime of ridicule and rejection by women.
</New>

<New PAsource="" >DI McTigue, who was in court for the second trial, said at the time: "He is the most dangerous man I have ever had anything to do with."
</New>

<New PAsource="" >Sarah's mum </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >Pat Rhodes </Verbatim>
<New PAsource="" >said last night: </New>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >"We feel there has been unfinished business while Smith </Verbatim>
<Rewrite PAsource="" >was </Rewrite>
<Verbatim PAsource="" >free."


</Verbatim>


